The only production for the start symbol is  
S → NT7 NT96.  
Hence the string derived by S must be the concatenation of a string from NT7 followed by a string from NT96.

The given string has length 3 (t1 t14 t5).  
Therefore NT7 must generate either 1 or 2 symbols and NT96 the remaining 2 or 1 symbols.

• NT7 has no terminal rule; its sole rule is NT7 → NT53 NT31, so the shortest string it can produce is length 2.  
• NT96 can produce one symbol via NT96 → 't4', or two or more symbols via NT96 → NT13 NT78 (both children produce at least one symbol).

Thus the only possible length split is 2 + 1, i.e. NT7 must generate the first two terminals and NT96 the last one.

However, the only one-symbol string NT96 can produce is 't4', not 't5'.  
Consequently NT96 cannot generate the last symbol of the target string, and no other split of lengths is possible.

Therefore the grammar cannot generate the string “t1 t14 t5”.

The first word of the string is the terminal ‘t7’.  
In the grammar the only non-terminal that can generate ‘t7’ is NT92:

 NT92 → 't7'

NT92 never appears as the left component of any binary rule; the only binary rule that contains NT92 is

 NT35 → NT43 NT92              (NT92 is the right component).

Consequently, any occurrence of NT92 in a derivation must be the right child of some NT35 whose left child (NT43) covers at least one token that precedes the ‘t7’.  
Because the very first token of the string is ‘t7’, there is no token before it. Hence no substring containing only the first token can be derived as NT35 → NT43 NT92, and there is no other way to incorporate NT92 (and therefore ‘t7’) into a larger derivation tree.

Therefore the grammar cannot derive a sentence that begins with ‘t7’, so it cannot generate the given string.

No

To generate any string the start symbol must use  

S → NT7 NT96  

so the right-most (last) terminal in every derivation is always produced by NT96.

NT96 has only two possible productions  

1. NT96 → 't4'        (generates exactly the single terminal t4)  
2. NT96 → NT13 NT78   (a binary production)

Case 1 would force the whole string to end with t4, but the given string ends with t28, so case 1 is impossible.

For Case 2 we must look at the right-most chain of non-terminals, because the last terminal of the whole string is always generated by the right-most child at every step:

NT96 ⇒ NT13 NT78  
                (last symbol comes from NT78)  
NT78 ⇒ NT31 NT65  
                (last symbol comes from NT65)  
NT65 ⇒ NT33 NT89  
                (last symbol comes from NT89)  
NT89 ⇒ NT51 NT36  
                (last symbol comes from NT36)  
NT36 ⇒ NT54 NT35  
                (last symbol comes from NT35)  

NT35 has only the two alternatives  
 a) NT35 → NT43 NT92    (last terminal from NT92 → t7 or t3)  
 b) NT35 → NT52 NT56    (last terminal from NT56 → t36)

Hence, no derivation using NT96 can ever end in t28; it can only end in t4, t7, t3 or t36.

Because the given string ends in t28, it cannot be produced by NT96 and therefore cannot be produced by the grammar at all.

Answer: No
